1176":"1176","1152":"1152","1260":"1260","um 1215":"about 1215","1219":"1219","1119":"1119","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Schottland, United Kingdom":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pollock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place in Glasgow, probably a British Celtic name derived from <i>pull-</i>, <i>poll-</i> ‘pool’ + a diminutive suffix. The surname has been established in northeast Ulster since the 17th century.","German: ethnic name for someone from Poland.","Americanized form of Jewish   Polak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pogue","meanings":["Irish (Cavan): shortened form of the Scottish name   Pollock   1, Gaelicized as <b>Polóc</b>, later assimilated to the Irish word <i>póg</i> ‘kiss’."]},{"name":"Pollick","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Pollock  . This surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Polič</b>, Croatian and Serbian <b>Polić</b> (see   Polich  ). Compare   Polick  ."]},{"name":"Palk","meanings":["English (Devon): shortened form of   Pollock  , with unrounding of the vowel to give <i>Palk</i>. Compare   Polk   and also   Pulford  . Derivation from a shortened form of the Middle English personal names <i>Palcok</i> and <i>Palkin</i> (pet forms of <i>Paul</i>) is formally possible, but no evidence has been found to substantiate this."]},{"name":"Paulk","meanings":["English (Devon) and Scottish: shortened form of   Pollock  . The Scottish name is a variant of   Polk  .","Altered form of a German surname, possibly   Paulke  ."]},{"name":"Polk","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   Pollock  .","Sorbian (<b>Półk</b> and <b>Pólk</b>): probably from a short form of a personal name based on Old Slavic <i>plъkъ</i> ‘crowd, army’ (see   Polka   3).","East German (of Slavic origin): variant of   Polke  ."]},{"name":"Pollok","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire): variant of   Pollock  ."]},{"name":"Polak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Miroslaw, Zbigniew, Boguslawa, Dorota, Jacek, Andrzej, Bogdan, Eugeniusz, Grzegorz, Irena, Jerzy, Jozef.","Polish and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Czech, Slovak, and Hungarian (<b>Polák</b>, Slovak also <b>Poľák</b>): ethnic name for someone from Poland (Polish <i>Polak</i>, Slovak archaic and Czech <i>Polák</i>). In the case of the Ashkenazic name, the reference is to a Jew from Poland. This surname is also found in Germany, where it is also of Sorbian origin (see 3 below), and in the Netherlands. Compare   Poliak  ,   Poljak  , and   Polyak  .","Slovenian and Croatian: topographic name for someone who lived in open country, derived from <i>polje</i> ‘field’, or a habitational name for someone from any of numerous places called Polje, named with this word. It may also be e.g. an occupational name for a field guard (see   Poljak  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Pollock III was born in 1152, in Renfrewshire, Scotland as the son of Robertus de Pollock II. He had at least 2 sons with Isabella. He died in 1219, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1119–1203":"1119–1203","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1176":"1176","1152":"1152","1260":"1260","um 1215":"umbes 1215","1219":"1219","1119":"1119","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Schottland, United Kingdom":"Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Kuollut","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1119–1203":"1119–1203","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1176":"1176","1152":"1152","1260":"1260","um 1215":"noin 1215","1219":"1219","1119":"1119","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Dumfriesshire, Schottland, United Kingdom":"Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1152–1219":"1152–1219","1176–Female":"1176–Décédée","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1119–1203":"1119–1203","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1176":"1176","1152":"1152","1260":"1260","um 1215":"environ 1215","1219":"1219","1119":"1119","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Écoss